  <p>Every year at the start of winter, the same thing happens across Melbourne: someone tries to light their wood heater for the first time in months, something goes wrong, and they end up with a room full of smoke or a fire that just won't stay alight. If that's you right now — or you want to avoid it — here's exactly how to light a wood heater properly, and what to do when it isn't working the way it should.</p>

  <h2>What You Need Before You Start</h2>

  <p><strong>Dry, seasoned firewood.</strong> This is the single most important factor in getting a fire going and keeping it burning well. Seasoned hardwood has been dried for at least 12 months and has a moisture content below 20%. Wet or green wood produces far more smoke, generates much less heat, and deposits creosote in the flue at a much faster rate. If you knock two pieces together and they make a dull thud rather than a sharp crack, they're probably not dry enough yet.</p>

  <p><strong>Dry kindling.</strong> Small sticks, dry twigs or commercial kindling. The kindling is what gets the heat up fast enough to establish the draw — skimping on kindling is one of the most common reasons fires fail to get going.</p>

  <p><strong>Fire starters or newspaper.</strong> Fire starters (the waxy blocks) are the most reliable option. Newspaper works fine but takes a bit more effort to get right. Never use accelerants — petrol, metho, lighter fluid — in a wood heater.</p>

  <p><strong>Matches or a lighter.</strong></p>

  <h2>Step-by-Step: How to Light a Wood Heater</h2>

  <p><strong>Step 1 — Open the air controls fully.</strong> Before you do anything else, open all the air vents on the heater completely. Most slow combustion heaters have a primary air control at the bottom and sometimes a secondary control. Both should be fully open for lighting. This gives the fire maximum oxygen to get established.</p>

  <p><strong>Step 2 — Check the damper if your heater has one.</strong> Some older heaters and most open fireplaces have a damper — a metal plate that controls airflow through the flue. Make sure it's fully open before lighting. A closed damper is a very common cause of smoke filling the room.</p>

  <p><strong>Step 3 — Prime the flue on cold mornings.</strong> This step is often skipped and it's the reason many first fires of the season fail. If the heater hasn't been used for weeks or months, the air inside the flue is cold and dense. Cold air falls — meaning there's a column of cold air sitting in your flue trying to come down into the room. If you light the fire without addressing this, the smoke hits that cold air and comes straight back into the room.</p>

  <p>To prime the flue: roll a piece of newspaper into a tight tube, light one end, and hold it inside the heater near the flue opening for 30–60 seconds. You'll feel the draw establish — the warm air starts pulling upward. Once you can feel that suction, the flue is primed and you're ready to light.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>Cold flue downdraught is most common on the first fire of the season, on very cold mornings, and in heaters where the flue runs on an external wall. Always prime a cold flue before lighting — it takes 60 seconds and prevents a room full of smoke.</p>
  </div>

  <p><strong>Step 4 — Build the fire correctly.</strong> There are two main methods: the traditional bottom-up build and the top-down build. The top-down method is more reliable for slow combustion heaters.</p>

  <p>For the top-down method: place two or three larger pieces of firewood on the bottom of the firebox. Stack kindling on top of the wood in a crisscross pattern, building up several layers. Place your fire starters or scrunched newspaper on top of the kindling stack. Light the top. The fire burns downward, generating heat rapidly and establishing draw before the larger logs catch.</p>

  <p>For the traditional method: place fire starters or newspaper at the base, build kindling in a crisscross over the top, then balance one or two smaller pieces of firewood over the kindling. Light the base.</p>

  <p><strong>Step 5 — Leave the door slightly ajar for the first few minutes.</strong> On many slow combustion heaters, leaving the door open a crack for the first 3–5 minutes while the fire establishes helps maintain airflow and gets the draw going. Check your heater's manual — some manufacturers specify this, others don't recommend it.</p>

  <p><strong>Step 6 — Add larger logs once the kindling is burning well.</strong> Don't add big logs too early. Wait until you have a good bed of flame and the kindling is fully alight, then add one or two pieces of seasoned hardwood. Don't overload the firebox — wood heaters burn most efficiently with adequate airspace between pieces.</p>

  <p><strong>Step 7 — Adjust the air controls.</strong> Once the fire is established and you've added your first load of hardwood, you can start reducing the air controls to slow the burn rate and improve efficiency. Don't close them down too quickly — wait until the fire is clearly burning well before restricting airflow.</p>

  <h2>Common Problems and How to Fix Them</h2>

  <h3>The fire won't stay alight</h3>

  <p>Almost always a firewood problem. Wet wood won't sustain combustion regardless of how well you build the fire. Check the moisture content — dry wood should feel light for its size, have visible cracks at the ends, and make a sharp sound when knocked together. If you don't have dry wood, you'll struggle until you do. Use more kindling and fire starters as a short-term workaround, but get properly seasoned wood sorted.</p>

  <h3>Smoke is coming back into the room</h3>

  <p>This is the most common complaint and it has several possible causes. Work through these in order:</p>

  <p>First, check the damper is open (if applicable). Second, prime the flue — cold flue downdraught is the most common cause on first fires of the season. Third, check the air controls are fully open. Fourth, crack a nearby window slightly — if draw immediately improves, your house is too tightly sealed and the heater is creating negative air pressure. Fifth, if none of the above works — the flue is almost certainly blocked or heavily sooted, which is preventing proper draw.</p>

  <h3>The fire lights but dies down quickly</h3>

  <p>Usually means the flue isn't drawing strongly enough to maintain combustion. Check the air controls are open. If the fire improves briefly when you open the heater door, restricted airflow through the flue is the issue — either a dirty flue, a partial blockage, or a house that's too airtight.</p>

  <h3>The heater gets very hot but the room doesn't warm up</h3>

  <p>Often a sign the air controls are too open — the fire is burning through wood very fast without giving the heat time to radiate. Reduce the air controls gradually once the fire is established. Also check that the room isn't losing heat through draughts, poorly sealed windows or inadequate insulation.</p>

