  <h2>When the Problem Is the Flue, Not the Fire</h2>

  <p>If you've worked through everything above — dry wood, primed flue, air controls open, damper open, tried cracking a window — and you're still getting smoke in the room or the fire simply won't establish, the flue is almost certainly the issue. The two most common flue problems are:</p>

  <p><strong>Creosote and soot buildup.</strong> After a season of use, the inside of the flue can be heavily coated with creosote and soot. This narrows the effective diameter of the flue, restricts airflow, and prevents proper draw. A flue that was fine at the end of last winter may have deteriorated enough over the warmer months that it's now struggling. This is by far the most common cause of draw problems in heaters that previously worked fine.</p>

  <p><strong>A bird nest or blockage.</strong> Unused chimneys are attractive nesting spots — particularly over spring and summer when the heater isn't running. A nest at the top of the flue can partially or completely block airflow. Signs of a nest include scratching sounds from the flue earlier in the year, twigs or debris in the firebox, and sudden severe smoke spillage on the first fire of the season.</p>

  <p>Both of these require a professional clean to fix. Don't try to burn through a blockage — it won't work and can start a chimney fire.</p>

  <h2>How to Keep Your Wood Heater Running Well All Winter</h2>

  <p><strong>Only burn dry, seasoned hardwood.</strong> Softwood, unseasoned wood and treated timber all cause problems — more smoke, more creosote, more call-outs. Melbourne's best firewood species include red gum, ironbark, messmate and stringybark. Buy from a reputable supplier and store it undercover with airflow.</p>

  <p><strong>Don't smoulder the fire overnight.</strong> Running the heater very slowly with restricted air overnight produces a lot of creosote. If you want the fire to last, load it with good hardwood and reduce the air slightly rather than closing it right down to a smoulder.</p>

  <p><strong>Clean the glass regularly.</strong> Black glass is a sign of incomplete combustion — usually wet wood or restricted airflow. Clean glass means the fire is burning efficiently.</p>

  <p><strong>Get the flue cleaned annually.</strong> Once a year — ideally in autumn before the heating season — is the standard for a heater used regularly through winter. It keeps the system safe, maintains draw, and is a requirement under most home insurance policies.</p>

  <h2>Quick Reference: Wood Heater Lighting Checklist</h2>

  <p>Before every fire: air controls fully open, damper open (if applicable), dry seasoned wood ready. On cold mornings or first fire of the season: prime the flue with a lit newspaper torch for 60 seconds before lighting. Build the fire: top-down method with fire starters on top of kindling, kindling on top of wood. Light, leave door slightly ajar for first few minutes, add larger logs once kindling is burning well. Adjust air controls down once fire is established.</p>

  <p>If smoke comes back in: check damper, prime flue, open a window to test for negative pressure. If still not drawing after all that — book a flue clean.</p>
